 13th century until the end of the medieval period. The personal name is of ancient Germanic origin, brought to England from France by the Normans; it is a shortened form of ancient Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>, which is composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>haid</i> ‘‘rank, worth’’."]},{"name":"Alicea","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Angel, Juan, Luis, Pedro, Julio, Rafael, Francisco, Ana, Jesus, Luz, Margarita.","Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico): probably a variant of   Alicia  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice or Alicia was born about 1240, in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She married William de Sandcroft about 1261, in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1240–UNKNOWN":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1266–Male":"1266–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1236":"1236","1266":"1266","1240":"1240","of Chepenhall, Fressingfield, Suffolk, England":"Fressingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1240–UNKNOWN":"noin 1240–Kuollut","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1266–Male":"1266–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","Abt 1240":"noin 1240","1236":"1236","1266":"1266","1240":"1240","of Chepenhall, Fressingfield, Suffolk, England":"Fressingfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1240–UNKNOWN":"environ 1240–Décédée","1236–Male":"1236–Décédé","1266–Male":"1266–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","Abt 1240":"environ 1240","1236":"1236","1266":"1266","1240":"1240","of Chepenhall, Fressingfield, Suffolk, England":"Fressingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Alice or Alicia est née environ 1240, à Fressingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé William de Sandcroft environ 1261, à Fressingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1240–UNKNOWN":"um 1240–Verstorben","1236–Male":"1236–Verstorben","1266–Male":"1266–Verstorben","1240–Female":"1240–Verstorben","Abt 1240":"um 1240","1236":"1236","1266":"1266","1240":"1240","of Chepenhall, Fressingfield, Suffolk, England":"Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Alice or Alicia wurde um 1240 in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hat um 1261 in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom William de Sandcroft geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn